<!-- WHY THIS AREA -->
<section style="background:var(--color-base, #f2ead4); padding:80px 24px;">
  <div style="max-width:800px; margin:0 auto;">
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:0.75rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.15em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#b98229; margin-bottom:1rem;">Local Expertise</p>
    <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif); font-size:clamp(1.8rem, 3.5vw, 2.8rem); font-weight:400; font-variation-settings:'opsz' 32; line-height:1.2; color:#191817; margin-bottom:1.75rem;">A heritage suburb four kilometres from the CBD, with rail, a growing professional market and character that sets it apart from generic inner north.</h2>
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      Albion is four kilometres north of the CBD in postcode 4010, with Albion Station on the Doomben line delivering a roughly 10-minute rail commute to the city. The suburb's character comes partly from its geography: bordered by Fortitude Valley to the south, Ascot to the east and Lutwyche and Windsor to the north, it occupies a position that is genuinely inner without being inner-city. The Albion Mills precinct and the heritage commercial warehouses along Sandgate Road have given the suburb a visual identity that distinguishes it from the standard Brisbane inner north formula. Behind the commercial strip, residential streets of original cottages and Queenslanders carry that same sense of accumulated character.
    </p>
<!-- APPRAISAL FORM -->
<div style="background:#fff; border-left:4px solid #b98229; padding:2rem 2rem 1.75rem; margin:2rem 0; border-radius:16px;">
